  "output": "## Summary\n\nThis is a static frontend (Vite + React + GSAP/Lenis + Framer Motion) ‚Äî no database or API layer, so classic N+1 *query* patterns don't apply. There is, however, a direct equivalent: a DOM-query loop that fires on every scroll frame. Details below, grouped as requested.\n\n### 1. N+1-equivalent: DOM queries repeated inside a per-frame scroll loop\n\n`WorkSection.tsx:169-191` ‚Äî `applyReveal()` is called from the ScrollTrigger's `onUpdate` (fires on essentially every scrub frame while scrolling) for every non-intro panel:\n\n```js\nconst applyReveal = (panel: HTMLElement, raw: number) => {\n  const hLines = panel.querySelectorAll<HTMLElement>('[data-frame-line=\"h\"]')\n  const vLines = panel.querySelectorAll<HTMLElement>('[data-frame-line=\"v\"]')\n  const videoWrap = panel.querySelector<HTMLElement>('[data-video-wrap]')\n  ...\n}\n```\n\n3 panels √ó 3 DOM queries √ó every scrub tick = the \"N+1\" here ‚Äî static elements re-queried on every frame instead of once. Cache them per panel at setup time:\n\n```js\nconst panelEls = panels.map((panel) => ({\n  panel,\n  hLines: panel.querySelectorAll<HTMLElement>('[data-frame-line=\"h\"]'),\n  vLines: panel.querySelectorAll<HTMLElement>('[data-frame-line=\"v\"]'),\n  videoWrap: panel.querySelector<HTMLElement>('[data-video-wrap]'),\n}))\n\nconst applyReveal = (entry: typeof panelEls[number], raw: number) => {\n  const t = easeOutCubic(clamp01(raw))\n  gsap.set(entry.hLines, { scaleX: t })\n  gsap.set(entry.vLines, { scaleY: t })\n  gsap.set(entry.videoWrap, { opacity: t, y: 60 * (1 - t), scale: 0.95 + 0.05 * t })\n  const video = entry.videoWrap?.querySelector('video') // could cache this too\n  ...\n}\n```\n\nBuild once outside `onUpdate`, reuse the cached refs inside it.\n\n### 2. Unnecessary re-renders\n\n`WorkSection.tsx:78-84` and `AboutSection.tsx` rebuild their translated data array **on every render**, including renders triggered by unrelated state (`watchHover` toggles on every video mouseenter/leave; `hovered` toggles on every service-list hover):\n\n```js\nconst projects: Project[] = projectKeys.map((key) => ({\n  n: key,\n  title: t(`work.projects.${key}.title`),\n  body: t(`work.projects.${key}.body`),\n  ...projectMeta[key],\n}))\n```\n\nFix ‚Äî memoize on `t` (which itself is stable per language, per `LanguageContext.tsx:44`):\n\n```js\nconst projects = useMemo(\n  () => projectKeys.map((key) => ({\n    n: key,\n    title: t(`work.projects.${key}.title`),\n    body: t(`work.projects.${key}.body`),\n    ...projectMeta[key],\n  })),\n  [t],\n)\n```\n\nSame fix applies to `services` in `AboutSection.tsx`.\n\n### 3. Caching opportunities\n\n- **Above fix** (memoize translated arrays) is the main one.\n- `Navbar.tsx` ‚Äî `spacer` and other DOM lookups are already correctly cached once outside the scroll handler (good pattern, already in place ‚Äî no change needed there).\n- Video elements in `WorkSection` use `preload=\"metadata\"` and defer `play()` until reveal ‚Äî already a good lazy-load pattern, no change needed.\n\n### 4. Memory leaks (minor, not severe)\n\n- `useMouseParallax.ts` and `HamburgerButton.tsx` create GSAP tweens (`quickTo`, `gsap.to`) but never call `.kill()` on unmount ‚Äî only event listeners are cleaned up. If the component unmounts mid-tween, the tween keeps running briefly against a detached node. Low impact (tweens are short and GC eventually), but the fix is one line:\n\n```js\nreturn () => {\n  window.removeEventListener('pointermove', onPointerMove)\n  gsap.killTweensOf([landscape, train]) // add this\n}\n```\n\n- Everything else checked (Preloader, ContactModal, VideoLightbox, CursorScroll, WorkSection's ScrollTriggers) properly kills timelines/timers/listeners on cleanup ‚Äî no leaks found there.\n- Already flagged by the codebase itself (`WorkSection.tsx:181-182`, `ponytail:` comment): off-screen panel videos keep decoding/playing after scrolling past. Already accepted debt with a documented upgrade path ‚Äî not re-litigating it here.\n\n### 5. Redundant computations\n\n`Navbar.tsx` ‚Äî `update()` runs on **every native `scroll` event**, unthrottled, and does `elementFromPoint` + a `getComputedStyle` walk up the DOM tree each time:\n\n```js\nwindow.addEventListener('scroll', update, { passive: true })\n```\n\n`getComputedStyle` forces a style recalculation ‚Äî doing this on every scroll event (which can fire many times per second under Lenis's momentum scrolling) is real, avoidable work. Gate it to one calculation per animation frame:\n\n```js\nlet ticking = false\nfunction onScroll() {\n  if (ticking) return\n  ticking = true\n  requestAnimationFrame(() => { update(); ticking = false })\n}\nwindow.addEventListener('scroll', onScroll, { passive: true })\n```\n\nSame rAF-gate is worth applying to `WorkSection.tsx:135` (`onScroll` re-checking `elementFromPoint` for the watch-hint) though its cost per call is much lower ‚Äî optional.\n\n**Priority order:** #1 (cache panel elements) and #2 (memoize translated arrays) are the real wins ‚Äî both fire on hot paths (scroll frame, hover). #4 and the Navbar throttle are cheap, low-risk cleanups.\n",
